Metabolism is commonly known as the biological process that sustains
and develops an organism.
Glycolysis, the metabolic pathway that converts glucose to pyruvate. From the Glycolysis page on Wikipedia, https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glycolysis
Simple system of equations
The consensus model for metabolism is a
system of stoichiometric equations, each with associated rates and metabolites. Data interpretation of such large systems is
often subject to high variation and models are subsequently hard to verify. Our research focuses on reliable techniques to consolidate models and data, in particular when applied to metabolism.
Sheaves enforce structure on data and track local values across the whole, making it easy to verify model fitness, even in error prone data
Difference in raw data and structured data, from prowebscraper. http://www.prowebscraper.com/blog/structured-vs-unstructured-data-best-thing-you-need-to-know/
1. Quantify error between mathematical model (stoichiometric equations) and real data (measured metabolite quantities)
How well do measured values (right) correspond with model (left)?
2. Find pieces of model that are least consistent with data. We expect these pieces may be missing something.
1., in green is a well tested component of a system which subsequently has small error. 2., in red is a newer addition that may be missing a key reaction step, metabolite, etc.
3. Verify analysis is reliable on large systems (many metabolites and many metabolic processes)
We want to be able to add new things without having to restart analysis
If we assign real data and real equations, we can quantify error between expectations in the model and real data values. We call the largest such error value the consistency radius.

Restrictions
We develop a structure and define relationships between the various reactions and metabolites involved in metabolism. The codomain is built to easily handle measured data.

Sheaves are functors that associate values and structure to systems of data. We associate values by mapping from objects (metabolites) to objects (real euclidean spaces). The structure is generated by creating a poset on the domain category, and the sheaf maps these inclusions to restriction morphisms (governed by equations).

flowRoot.flowPara: We tested two simulated data sets on the same simple system of equations. The first data set corresponds to a normal distribution of data values around our predicted values. We expect the consistency radius for this data to be small. Second, we tested data generated by a slightly modified set of equations, adding one intermediary step before reaching the final measurement. Here, we expect a high error. Note - we used the Pysheaf library to help conduct tests.
Sheaves can be used to interpret valuable informaion about model fitness, and directly satisfy all three of our research objectives.
First, they provide a versatile methodology to quantify errror between mathematical models and real data (Consistency Radius).
Second, they provide diagnostic information into where predictions likely deviate from measurements (Different error values on restrictions).
Finally, we note the sheaf structure is easily modified to include increasingly large systems or models.

While we focused mainly on metabolism, we remark on the versatility of sheaves, and note the sheaf structure used in this presentation can be modified slightly to model and quantify error in the following, to name a few -
Systems of differential equations (Disease spread, many physical systems)
Transformations (Special Relativity)
Interesting Future Questions
How could we incorporate statistics/confidence-intervals for deciding if a measurement is 'close enough'?
Are sheaves a useful tool to measure error propogation?

An iterative process called a 'consistency radius filtration', where we increase allowed error and slowly see more and more of the codomain category can be used to easily understand error distribution in a system.
Also, implementing techniques for finding the nearest global section, we can find ideal data that would minimize error in the system.
